Fourteen of the All Progressives Congress (APC) governorship aspirants in Cross River State have reportedly accepted Senator Bassey Otu as the consensus candidate of the party. They came up with the arrangement in the early hours of Tuesday after a meeting of key stakeholders in Abuja presided over by Governor Ben Ayade, The Nation gathered. Ayade was said to have begged the stakeholders to unite and present a consensus aspirant from the South. The Governor reportedly picked Otu, stating acceptability and popularity were responsible for the choice. The Nation gathered other aspirants, including Arch. Bassey Eyo Ndem, Prof. Eyo Etim Nyong, Asuquo Ekpeyong Jnr, Engr. Ben Akak, Engr. Nsa Ekpeyong Asuquo, Chief Ogbang Ebock and a host of others mostly from the southern senatorial district conceded to the choice. But two aspirants, Senator John Owan-Enoh and Chief Chris Agara, from the central senatorial district, refused the consensus arrangement instantly.   Kaduna: NDLEA arrests 302 suspected drug traffickers inâ€¦     Rainstorm kills five, injures 42 in Damaturu     BREAKING: Parties urge INEC to alter 2023 poll timetable   They were said to have insisted that they have to consult their supporters before making a final decision. The Nation gathered that Agara and Owan-Enoh defied appeal from the party that no one should buy the nomination form until the party concludes arrangements for a possible consensus candidate. Agara particularly told the meeting over 100 delegates and party members had endorsed his nomination form and he has to get to them first. Owan-Enoh was reported to have said the same thing. When contacted, Cross River APC chairman, Alphonsus Eba, said he was in another meeting and will call back. But he was yet to get back as of the time of filing this report.